**Course Number and Name:** CST 206 \- *Data Science*  
**Term Dates:** Section Start Date \- Section End Date  
**Meeting Location:** Section Meeting Building Section Meeting Room  
**Meeting Days & Times:** Section Meeting Days; Section Start Time \- Section End Time  
**Lecture/Lab Hours:** 2.00 Lecture Hours and 2.00 Lab Hours  
**Credits:** 3.00  
**Prerequisite(s):** ENG 097, MAT 144, and CST 161\.  
**Course Description:** This course

## Course Learning Outcomes

**Upon successful completion of this course, students will be able to:**

1. Utilize essential tools and environments for Python-based Data Science development, including Google CoLab, Visual Studio Code, and GitHub.  
2. Utilize foundational tools like NumPy, SciPy, and Pandas, demonstrating competence in their application for data manipulation, analysis and processing.  
3. Perform exploratory data analysis and generate data visualizations using Matplotlib.  
4. Apply mathematical foundations to understand how data transformations and model dynamics work in practice.  
5. Design and evaluate machine learning models.  
6. Construct and deploy a simple Full-Stack web application integrating a Data Science model using Flask.  
7. Explain the basic structure and application of Large Language Models.  
8. Collaborate in teams to build, document and present a working Data Science solution.

## Experiential Learning

Students will complete a semester-long, team-based Data Science project that applies course concepts to a real-world problem. This project will require students to collect, clean, analyze, and model data using industry-standard tools such as Python, Pandas, and Scikit-learn. The final deliverable will be a deployable Full-Stack application using Flask, presented through GitHub, Visual Studio Code and a live demonstration.

This experiential learning activity bridges academic theory with career-ready skills, emphasizing critical thinking, quantitative analysis and collaborative problem-solving. It supports general education outcomes including scientific reasoning, technological competency, and effective oral and written communication through regular team documentation, peer collaboration, and a final group presentation.

| ----- | ----- | ----- |
| Utilize essential tools and environments for Python-based Data Science development, including Google CoLab, Visual Studio Code, and GitHub | Hands-on setup of Google CoLab, and Visual Studio Code. GitHub cloning, commits, pushing and branching. | Homework 1 verifies the completion of setup. GitHub repository checks. |
| Utilize foundational tools like NumPy, SciPy, and Pandas, demonstrating competence in their application for data manipulation, analysis and processing. | Conduct hands-on workshops and project-based learning activities where students learn to utilize foundational tools like NumPy, SciPy, and Pandas for data manipulation, analysis, and processing tasks, fostering competence through practical application. | Project Assessments. Algorithm Visualization Analysis. Written. Presentation and Discussion. Peer/Case Review. |
| Perform exploratory data analysis and generate data visualizations using Matplotlib. | EDA labs using real datasets, where students explore variable distributions, correlations and missing data patterns. Visualization tutorial and critique. | Visualization-based assignment, EDA lab, and instructor rubric for lab. |

| Explain the basic structure and application of Large Language Models.  | Introduction to HuggingFace, exploration of input/output structure and tokenization, and exploration of transformer architecture. | Homework on prompt engineering, in-class group discussion and mini-demo |
| Collaborate in teams to build, document and present a working Data Science solution.  | Semester-Long group project, weekly check-ins, GitHub collaboration, team roles defined, and presentation preparation. | Group project presentation, GitHub log review, peer evaluation form, and instructor grading rubric. |
